Text: The goals for this week were to finish our written project proposal and perhaps do some initial work on our project - for me, that was playing around with web scraping on R or Python or whatever language was necessary.
Because I was taught web scraping in COMP120, navigating R to do this task is essentially a no-brainer for me.

Now - the issue with this is that Susu doesn't want to use R.  I think she may have been traumatised from using R in her last studio project, but, I feel as though it would be okay, because if I undergo all the web scraping, she won't have to touch R.  After all, I asked her if she would like to undergo some web scraping and that is why she doesn't want to use R.  If so, I am willing to compromise andÂ  learn it in another language, however, she says she doesn't plan on doing any web scraping.
So, at this point Teacher1 has introduced web scraping through Excel to us.
I am happy to do it through excel if it makes her happy.
However, since we are both Mac users we have found that PowerQuery is not available on Excel for Mac users.
Yet again, a bump in the road - but we can do the scraping through student desktop.
Now, to reflect upon this situation - if I am honest, it is disheartening to not have some compromisation on Susu's end.
I am trying to understand her thoughts about it and maybe she is concerned that the client won't know how to use R so that is why she is always pushing for an alternative language.
I thought that perhaps in our deliverables we could describe web scraping using Excel for Kevin, as an alternative (backup) solution.
Overall, I am still likely to web scrape through R, because this is the area I want to develop my learning/skill and what I am most comfortable and confident in doing.
Perhaps on the side too, I will do some web scraping through Excel to satisfy Susu and understand this method in preparation to describe to our client.
Guess we will see how this new week goes hehe!
